The two-stage military trigger, detachable box magazine, op-rod and roller cam bolt call to mind the rich history of the M1A™ while providing functional ease of operation and legendary reliability. You may be looking for a special addition to your collection, or you may be looking for a hard-working rifle that will pull duty on the range, in the treestand or in your truck. This is a great starter pack if your just getting into firearms or not, still a great kit.

For those of you who call me to purchase and don't understand the new (not that new, but A TON of people still call me and get intimated with the process.) regulations in WA state:

Please don't call if you are not willing to complete each of the steps. The process is straightforward and as long as you don't have a criminal record, you will be fine.

1. If you want the gun, you will need to meet me at an FFL. I use one on Wetmore Ave in Everett, because they charge only $25. I would like to use this FFL as I will be covering the fee.
2. Once at the FFL, if you like the gun, you pay me. Once you hand me the money. I pay for the background check. At this point the sale is final, as I am paying for the background check.
3. The FFL will make the background check phone call. If you have no criminal history you have nothing to worry about.You will get your gun, you may just need to wait a few days. This is when a CPL comes in handy because you've already had a background check done, and it speeds the process.
4. If FFL tells you that you need to wait, the FFL will simply hold the firearm until they get the ok from the cleared background check. At that point you pickup the gun and owe nothing.

Please don't lowball me. The price is firm. There is already $150 worth of ammo, 3 magazines: 2 ten round and 1 15 round AND the Blackhawk Serpa holster included. You can keep the green ammo can currently holding all the ammo.

title: For Sale:  BRAND NEW KEL-TEC KSG 12
postcontent:
Brand New Kel-Tec KSG 12 $789.00
(Background & TN Tax)
DESCRIPTION:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

What is really surprising is that this Glock hand cannon fires a round that puts a .45 acp round to shame yet is NOT punishing to shoot. I fire 100 rounds of the ammo I plan to use for home defense through each of my home defense pistols, clean them, and then load them and stash them in strategic places in my home. 

For various reasons, I no longer need 3 of these man droppers stashed in my home. No Glock 29 I've ever owned has ever failed to chamber any defense ammo nor failed to fire. Since they certainly are not pretty, they have to be the ultimate in reliable and dependable along with being world class accurate for a compact pistol. I have added Meprolight TFO sights to all of my self protection firearms. The sights are NOT cheap, but they are the brightest sights you can buy for daytime as well as night time shooting. 

This pistol comes in Glock box, owners manual and two 10 round magazines that both have the Pierce pinky grip extension. As you can see in the picture, he original Glock copper lube stuff is still on this pistol. If you want a man dropper, and not a pistol that may just possibly dissuade any intruder, this is for you. The night sights are less than 2 years old, so you should get at least 10 more years out of them before they dim.  If you want the pistol without the TFO sights on it, I own the $600 sight pressing machine and can put the original sights back on for $50 less.

The package deal for this home protection system is $525 with all pictured and with the TFO sights. I will need to see proper Indiana ID and preferably a carry permit. postcontent:
Fairbairn-Sykes Pattern Three Knife.   I bought this knife in the late fifties and believe it is a genuine Third Pattern, or P-3, because of the following features.  The blade is the “thick” type, showing triangular flats where it was reduced in thickness to enter the guard.  The guard itself is thick with sharp edges.  It appears to carry three stamps, unfortunately all in the same place.  One is clearly “ENGLAND” and the second (over the first) is a broad arrowhead.  Above the arrowhead point, there appears to be a third stamp, which might be a “2.”   The pommel carries a barely visible “2” stamp near the hilt.  The sheath is stamped with the word “ENGLAND” near the hilt.
The blade has been sharpened and is discolored but there is no rust.  The copper tip on the sheath has a slight dent at the end, but does not interfere with knife insertion.
